<section xml:id="sec-intro-to-exponential-functions" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Intro to Exponential Functions</title>
  
  <introduction>
    <example>
      <title>Graph of <m>f(x) = 2^x</m></title>
      <p>
        Consider the graph of <m>f(x) = 2^x</m>. First, create a table of values, using <m>x</m>-values of <m>-2, -1, 0, 1</m>, and 2, and plugging them into the equation.
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>
          \begin{array}{c|l}
          x \amp f(x) \\
          \hline
          -2 \amp 2^{-2} = \frac{1}{4} = 0.25 \\[4pt]
          -1 \amp 2^{-1} = \frac{1}{2} = 0.5 \\[4pt]
          0 \amp 2^0 = 1 \\
          1 \amp 2^1 = 2 \\
          2 \amp 2^2 = 4
          \end{array}
        </mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        Then, connect these points with a smooth curve. Here is a graph: <url href="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/ckryy4hneu">Graph of <m>f(x)=2^x</m></url>. Observe the <m>y</m>-values of <m>0.25, 0.5, 1, 2, 4</m>. Notice that each time <m>x</m> increases by 1, <m>y</m> is multiplied by 2.
      </p>
